Anyway, we assume it's about Higgs, as the chances of being wrong seem few.
There is, in this great world, a widespread and inescapable law that implies that two things cannot be found in the same place at the same time.
There's no way to break that rule and don't try too hard, because it'll end up hurting itself.
Although particle physics is a very complex world, it has been shown that there is also a law of these characteristics: the principle of exclusion of Pauli, which stipulates that two particles cannot occupy the same space at the same time if they are in the same "quantum state"; a "state" that consists, in general, of some of its characteristics.
The physicists classify the particles into two categories.
On the one hand we meet the good citizens called fermions, who wisely obey the beginning of Pauli.
And on the other hand there are the bosons, a dirty panda of anarchists who have no respect for anything, or at least not for this principle, which means that they can be found in the same place and at the same time.
According to the Berkeley Labs' web page The Particle Adventure which, by the way, is extraordinary, the bosons are divided into two groups: the mesons, of which we will not speak here, and the "particles of force", by which the great forces of nature spread and with which the Higgs boson would somehow be related.
These bosons, I could underline here, are not the exotic bugs we could believe.
In fact, if you can read this chronicle, it is thanks to an extraordinarily banal boson: the photon or the "particle of light" that acts as "messenger" of electromagnetic force.
Indeed, when a particle with an electric charge accelerates or changes direction, it "disorders" the electromagnetic field in that precise environment; a little like when we throw a stone at a pond.
In this "disorder" an electromagnetic wave (from light, infrared, ultraviolet, etc.) is born, and this wave is nothing but a photon; that is, one of the bosons "power bearers".
More stable field
The same happens with the Higgs boson, with the difference that it is another field, the Higgs field, which needs to be "disordered" for this boson to appear.
Now, the Higgs field is much more stable than the electromagnetic field. To activate it, it takes to reach extremely high energies, a little as if it were an ice-cold pond in which only a thick rock could slide through the surface.
That's why it takes a huge particle accelerator like the CERN (the great Hadron Collisioner is a ring of 27 km of circumference!) to achieve such energy levels.
