Bitcoin differs from other systems with types of virtual coins such as "credits", used to advance in a video game and that can be won playing or can be bought (and even occasionally redeem).
The Facebook social network also developed this type of system.
But in every exchange a central authority controls and treats the changes.
With bitcoin, all network nodes are both depositories of accounting books, verifiers, money issuers and buyers and sellers.
How does that network work?
Each transaction between two users is actually made between two e-mail addresses in the form of an e-mail.
A user can choose a different address for each payment, thus guaranteeing anonymity.
A set of information linked to this transaction is signed electronically through a double key encryption system.
The network can thus verify the authenticity of the transaction.
Thanks to the content of the file, it is also possible to ensure that bitcoins changes consist of the public account book, which is disseminated throughout the network.
The key milestone is to write that new transaction in that book.
This goes through the resolution of a mathematical challenge to computers and the winner, a sort of temporary central banker, will have the privilege of adding that complementary line.
This is a phase of file cutting, i.e. transformation of a large file into a shorter and more unique numerical footprint.
Computers "take" the new transaction and add a number before "trace" the set.
The goal is to find the number that offers a particular footprint (more zeros at first).
Once that number is found, the other nodes easily verify that it is the good one.
The transaction is then indestructibly linked to the chain of sets of the other transactions; any modification would change the footprint.
If, to commit a fraud, one user would want to pay twice with the same money very quickly (in less than ten minutes), the network would only accept as valid one of the two transactions; the other would stay orphaned, as both have different fingerprints.
The computer that solves the challenge takes 50 bitcoins.
To avoid inflation, this reward is divided into two regulars, probably before the end of 2012.
The number of bitcoins in circulation is therefore limited to 21 million, but they are divisible up to a hundred millionth, leaving a wide margin.
The difficulty of this challenge is also revealed in each increase in computing power.
The life of the network already has its ups and downs.
Websites offering services for Bitcoin have been attacked and bitcoins have been stolen in storage.
"The fault used does not affect the same protocol," says Pierre Noizat, who just launched Paymium, a real currency payment company using the Bitcoin network.
The ECB also takes into account the potential for money laundering through this anonymous service.
