Pierre Noizat, author of a pedagogic book on this coin, believes quite in the potential of this technology in addition to the transaction network.
Your system, Paytunia, is equivalent to a credit card (in real currency) or a mobile payment without contact, but uses Bitcoin to validate transactions, which thus come out cheaper.
The carrier also manages his identity and can therefore remain anonymous.
The system is easy to start up in shops, which do not have to install new terminals or software.
They simply provide an address that a phone can "photograph and recognize", says Pierre Noizat, who ensures that he has thousands of users.
There is a general movement to review hierarchical systems by more horizontal systems.
"It will take some time for Bitcoin to impose, but in 2013 there could be a change," he predicts.
Moreover, in its report, the ECB plans to reassess the various risks, which are now considered high, in the event that this currency is successful.
