Employees of fast food restaurants and supermarkets in the US are on strike.
Up to a quarter of American teens find their first jobs as cashiers in "McDonald's"
In recent days, a wave of protests against low wages has been launched in the United States at Walmart Corporation supermarkets and restaurants in popular fast food chains such as "McDonald's", "Burger King", "Taco Bell", "Wendy's" and "Kentucky Fried Chicken".
For now no one dares to assert whether or not this wave will come to the nine points, or whether it is destined to lose strength and to soften in its early stages.
Protest actions are supported by trade unions and a number of left-wing NGOs.
In addition to the increase in the modest wages received by Walmart workers and those of the fast food system, the aim of the protest organizers is to create workers' unions in these companies.
For now, this sector of the economy has practically not been occupied by the trade union movement.
Forty-six cents a year?
The actions began last week, after Thanksgiving, the so-called "Black Friday." On that day, in the United States, the orgy of discounts that captured millions of inhabitants, and that was sometimes accompanied by confrontations.
On that day, some Walmart Corporation workers, employing 2.2 million people around the world, left their jobs and formed protest pickets alongside trade unions and left-wing activists in the corporation's stores, whose products are aimed at low-income and moderate-income people.
Walmart sells everything, from diapers, hunting rifles and car batteries, to vacuum cleaners, eggs and milk.
The products in your stores are on average between 8% and 27% cheaper than those in the largest supermarkets.
That's why many underpaid Walmart workers buy only at work.
The availability and assortment of products have made Walmart one of America's largest corporations.
According to the words of two critics, Walmart can afford to sell products at very low prices, partly because he pays little to his workers.
The latter also complain about poor working conditions, such as the lack of mounts or hand scanners.
This "Black Friday" the participants of the demonstration demanded an increase in wages and complained that the cost of health insurance provided by the corporation increased from $30 to $100 per month.
For a typical Walmart worker, who receives $9.5 per hour, this spending is excessive, they said.
Scientists at the University of California in Berkeley argue that if Walmart increases the average salary up to $12 per hour, this will cost the corporation $3.2 trillion.
This is about 1.1% more than it spends on wages now.
If Walmart puts the wage increase on consumers' shoulders, every visit to the store will result in only 46 cents more expensive.
In one year they will spend the ridiculous amount of $12.39 more than they spend now.
Walmart's supporters are satisfied that the protest took place only in nine states and did not cause any loss to the corporation.
The "Black Friday" was extended in its stores from 8 p.m. on Thursday to midnight on the following day and, during that time, Walmart sold about 5000 items per second.
In total, their cash registers carried out the "Black Fridays" almost 100 million transactions.
The company's representative, Dan Fogelman, stated in an interview with the left-wing website Huffington Post, that they left their job "less than five" Walmart employees and that the protest had only been "another public relations trick," organized by the workers' union.
"Free box!"
The protests continued this week in New York, in which the objectives were not precisely the Walmart department stores (which in this progressive city have no appreciation, and that is why for now there are none), but the "McDonald's" and other cheap restaurants.
McDonald's says he sells billions of portions, and then they don't even give you the sick leave and they don't pay you for your honest work!
Jumaane Williams, Member of the New York City Council
Currently, according to federal and New York law, the minimum wage is $7.25 per hour.
Fast food restaurants are increasing over time, but only slightly, and on average, ordinary workers receive $8.90 per hour in New York City.
No one wins less than they do in this city.
How it is possible to survive in New York with that money, for me it is something incomprehensible.
There was a time when almost a quarter of American teenagers went through the McDonalds and worked there, behind the counters, part-time after school, even though they still lived with their parents.
Few saw this as the main source of income or planned to stay there for a long time.
Now, I constantly stumble in some interviews with McDonald's workers who complain that they have to live on this salary, and sometimes even feed their children.
On the other hand, in a Wall Street Journal forum there is a comment whose author points out that it is irresponsible to have children if he does not know what to eat with.
Participants in the protests, which began at 6:30 a.m. on Thursday morning at McDonald's on 40th Street and Madison Avenue, demanded that cashiers and cooks of fast food be started paying at least $15 an hour, i.e. that their current minimum wage be doubled.
They also demanded that workers' unions be established in the fast food sector.
U.S. law prohibits the administration from preventing this right and punishing the activists of the trade union movement with harassment and dismissals.
On the other hand, administration rarely makes life easier for them.
But for objective reasons, it is easy for unions to cover the fast food sector.
One of the main factors is the excessive turnover of staff.
Disagreements
Noisy protests took place that same day at other cheap restaurants in Manhattan.
The culmination of the action took place in the middle of the rally at McDonald's near Times Square, in which several local democrat politicians participated, in particular the City Council member Jumaane Williams, who said: "McDonald's says he's selling billions of portions, and then he doesn't even give you a hospital or pay you for your honest work."
The protesters received the support of other prominent New York Democrats, for example the candidate for mayor of the city Bill de Blasio, who said that "we must support workers in the fast food sector to achieve fair wages and the economic prosperity that each New Yorker deserves."
As described in the New York Times, this has been the biggest manifestation of this kind in American fast food history.
But in it only a few hundred people participated, even not all of them were employees of the fast food service, in which tens of thousands of people in New York worked.
It is not yet clear whether this will serve as a spark to provoke a massive movement.
"For now, deceiving the brain is not so easy"
The theme of augmented reality, so popular among fans of modern technologies, has recently been perceived with normality mainly through the prism of special glasses.
At the beginning of the summer, at its annual Google conference it demonstrated a moving model and later, in November, it was known that Microsoft had also submitted an application to claim the corresponding patent.
However, from a conversation with the head of the 3D interactive technology group at the Microsoft laboratory in Cambridge, Izadi Sharamom, it was diluted that for the scientists of that company, the glasses already belonged to a past stage.
They are attracted to the perspective of manipulating virtual objects in the air with bare hands and creating open virtual spaces.
- Please, in general terms, what is the subject of your research group's study?
- We dedicate ourselves to the interaction person-computer, but we also try to extend the limits of this interaction.
For now humanity in its great mass has been trapped in the work stage with the pixels of the flat screen, sometimes touching it with the finger.
But we want to look 5-10 years ahead and guess the cardinal changes in this interaction.
For example, the Xbox console and Kinect sensors represent a step forward and today no Xbox is sold without Kinect, as everyone is interested in gesture control.
- What else is there for us in the future?
- Although Kinect has led the interaction to the physical level, much of it still occurs on a flat screen, sometimes in 3D.
The introduction of information has improved (the system receives more data), and the output is not yet very good.
We are trying to change this, we work on truly three-dimensional visualization systems, based on different technologies, including design.
The world must be freed from computing to ours, to the physical, to make it more tangible.
For this, however, it is necessary to recognize not only the user, but also the space around him.
Then we can complete the real world with virtual objects in a more comfortable way.
First of all, fuck those silly virtual reality helmets!
- What do you think about voice control?
A very popular detail, but don't you think they overestimate it?
- Of course you cannot be considered a panacea, it remains pending to resolve the question of privacy, as it is not always desired that others learn about our actions and intentions.
In fact, all types of interaction with computers are good, but each in its own field.
For example, for the control of devices in public places, we had a project where we thought about gestures, but not loose movements, but shorter ones.
In addition, the gestures were captured not by the camera of the device, but by a bracelet recording the movement of the bones and muscles.
For now it is very large, but in theory it can be reduced to the size of a wristwatch.
But in general, the future is for a combined type of control, e.g. gesture + voice.
- How's that?
- For example, how would you ask me to pass you this soda can?
You'll talk and show it at the same time.
- Normally I just talk.
- Oh, that's gonna be very hard to recognize.
- I mean, do you want to force users to adapt to what the machine can or can't do right now?
- Not necessarily, but it's a mutual rapprochement.
I think in the near future we will have to work mainly on designing new types of sensors that can accurately determine the person's reactions.
These can be, for example, laser sensors, as they provide a good in-depth resolution, which is very important.
- If we talk about your work with Xbox Kinect sensors, what complaints do you have about modern cameras?
Do you lack resolution, depth or anything else?
- In principle, the present generation is what can be the beginning of our work with three-dimensional recognition.
Of course, it would be nice to get 8 megapixels at 1000 fps speed.
But the question is not in the megapixels, but in the quality of the matrix and in depth.
From this latter point of view, all current technologies are not good enough for us; this gives more work to algorithm designers.
I mean, we have to remember not only the resolution on the X and Y axes, but also on Z.
Speed is also important, the number of frames per second.
Human movements are quite dynamic and the current 30 fps are really scarce, especially for gestures.
Steven Bathiche, of our lab in Redmond, made a contact sensor with adjustable processing delay of 1 to 100 ms and it should be mentioned that the modern sensors produced in series are closer to the second value (60-100).
Not everyone understands to what extent this affects man-machine interaction.
It would be very useful to me for my work an equivalent of such a device, but that I do not require contact so that the tables per second are more.
- And you don't need to increase the number of cameras?
- The Kinect now has three "cameras", one of which is in fact the infrared transmitter and the second the signal receiver reflected.
But the third camera is actually a simple sensor of the visible diaphragm.
This is not used to determine the depth of the object.
Potentially, more cameras could solve the problem...
Or, on the contrary, increase it and increase the required amount of calculations.
It would be good to create a flexible Kinect analog, play with the camera location curvature and see how this would help determine the three-dimensional position.
- As far as I can remember, Microsoft, unlike Google, has not presented its glasses to the public.
Don't you think that from the point of view of the daily use of augmented reality technologies, glasses are one of the most visible platforms?
- Of course, spending all the time holding up a smartphone in your hands, it's not very comfortable, but I think: the best option would be an augmented reality "transmutable" when, based on a cloud platform, you could switch from glasses to smartphone,
The glasses are very personal devices, in that is your strength (private things only you can see them), but also your weakness: an augmented reality based on glasses will not allow you to work on virtual objects along with other people.
- Imagine for a moment that the manipulation of virtual holographic objects in the air is available not only for Tony Stark of the film "Iron Man", but also for any mere mortal.
There is a problem in this idea that critics often point out: there is no tactile answer!
Hands don't feel anything!
What answers does your group prepare for this challenge?
- In my lectures I often say that augmented reality is the seventh burst in the interaction between man and machine.
I think the eighth one might as well be the addition of tactile sensations.
Meanwhile, one of the most interesting tricks is the use of the second hand as a support for the image.
Record the touch perfectly!
But there are also technologies that are truly oriented to bring tangibleity to these "images in the air." For example, interference with several ultrasonic rays directed at a specific point where the finger is located gives a similar feeling to what you feel if someone was blowing it in the yolks of your fingers, but that feeling is still very weak.
There are also wrist bracelets that influence the nerve endings of the fingers, this also a promising direction.
- Have you tried to trick the brain?
Make him think he feels what he looks like he should feel the moment he sees something?
- That's a good idea, we haven't tried yet.
Here is hidden another challenge with which we will have to fight for a long time, how to make a person physically located in a very small space believe he goes to an open space, almost endless. We are also working on the idea of running tapes (not like those of gyms), mobile platforms, as well as giant balloons.
For now, deceiving the brain is not so easy, we still have to work for many years.
That's what makes work attractive to researchers with virtual reality, which many things are in a state of total conception.
