How does the control system work in Germany?
Is it an office similar to our NKU or is it organized differently?
As for the offices, like the NKU, there acts the Bundesrechnungshof (Federal Court of Accounts), with an organization similar to ours, with a school as well, the only thing is that in your case it is structured in a somewhat different way, but in principle both offices evolve parallelly.
The powers are also to some extent analogous, however, while Germany has a federal organization, the courts of account are even at this level. In this aspect it differs slightly from our system.
The Federal Court of Auditors (BRH) can only control federal money, which we call state funds here.
The public funds, which are administered by the regions and municipalities, there, in Germany, are controlled in the Federal Court of Auditors.
As for local legislation, is it simpler than ours?
I would generally not like to draw up a comparison without specific data, but Germany remains a model in some respects, but it cannot be accurately explained what is best.
Could it be better, for example, with regard to the quality of inspectors?
That's for sure not, but, I repeat, I don't like to make these kind of comparisons.
It must be said that even those countries that we take as a model must face a large number of problems.
If it weren't, it wouldn't be beneficial for you to work with our office, would it?
With regard to our country's legislation, what did the amendment of the law on public procurement mean to your Office? Is it in any way manifest its impact?
Given that the period of validity of this amendment is relatively short, it has not yet been stated in the control proceedings.
Since we carry out ex post controls, there is a certain delay.
For now, it is observed in the process of preparing future controls: we have started a new tool of "non-economic risk detection", which we have put in place almost 14,000 public tenders, which have been analysed. The changes will be perfectly reflected here, as the limits are modified, the conditions of some types of the selection process are rectified and similar.
Do you consider the adoption of this law to be beneficial, or rather, a hindrance to the bureaucratic system?
I think this law is surely a step in the right direction and I hope so.
The problem that may arise is that regulations "harden up" and that it is impossible to comply with them.
Under previous regulations, controlled persons were linked to the contractor (e.g. in the case of regional operational programmes of the Regional Council), and each law not respected in the area of public procurement meant a breach of budgetary discipline.
Does it make sense then to harden the law this way?
I don't think so.
The system should exclude those who want to attack or take advantage of it and not punish those who make a formal decision, which has no impact on decision-making.
A system of this kind will only be able to create greater bureaucratic pressure.
And how does he get out of this?
We'll see where this started road leads us.
The Prime Minister has recently stated that the SDG would not disturb entrepreneurs with controls of the so-called švarc system, with reference to being autonomous only on paper. What does this mean?
Is the švarc system prohibited or permitted?
The law must be regulated in some way, and if it prohibits anything, then even the Prime Minister of the Government cannot prevent the Office from acting, which is under an obligation to carry out such controls and to demand obligations.
You can say, "We change the law and allow it," but you can't say we'll do anything.
In the Public Procurement Act, the rules are quite strict as to how to act formally, and that is how it should be in order to protect public competition.
But, on the other hand, it is tragic that the candidate with the best offer is excluded from meeting the formal requirements.
The law will never be perfect, but its application must be correct. This, in my opinion, is what we lack.
