Poland and the cosmos.
At last week's meeting of ministers of the countries of the European Space Agency, Poland was accepted as the twelfth member of ESA. It is the second member of ESA of the former Eastern European bloc, after the Czech Republic, which became a full member on 12 November 2008.
Poland began intensive collaboration with ESA in 1994 and during subsequent years participated in the agency's project commission.
However, Poland's path to the cosmos began long before.
Polish enthusiasts were already engaged in space flights before World War II, although their work was not always understood.
I remember, for example, A. Šternfeld's conference at Warsaw's astronomical observatory in which, on 6 December 1933, he presented his ideas on the pioneering study "Introduction to cosmonautics".
The ideas of the young engineer (born 1905) left the assistants indifferent and, years later, Šternfeld remembered that Dr. Jan Gadomski had been the only one who had shown interest in his work.
In 1934 Šternfeld won in France the Robert Esnault-Pelterie and André Louis Hirsch Award for his "Introduction to the Cosmonautics".
Dr. Jan Gadomski (1899 - 1966), mentioned above, later became a major driver of astronomy and cosmonautics.
He published hundreds of articles in Polish magazines and wrote a series of books dedicated to this scientific discipline.
Gadomski became a promoter of cosmonautics, was known all over the world and his contribution to science was rewarded when he put his name on one of the craters of the hidden face of the moon.
Already in 1925 a drain was built in Poland, which was to be supplied with a rocket engine.
Regrettably, the author of the proposal is unknown and the details of the project are not known.
It is not clear whether the rocket was to be used for the start of the dresin or for its braking.
The information about this dresina is limited to the collection in the press of the time.
From 1933 Polish artillery began to engage in missiles.
The research was funded by Komórka Techniki Uzbrojenia in collaboration with Prof. Mieczyslawem Wolfkem and Prof. Gustawem Mokrzyckiegim.
From the material preserved, it is evident that the investigation reached the stage of the practical tests.
However, with the arrival of the German troops, the investigation was interrupted.
In 1937 the prototype of a photoelectric hunting missile designed by engineer Rohoziński appeared in the specialized press and the following year the study "Rakieta - torpedoe powietrzna i rakietobomba lotnicza" by author Leliwa-Krzywoblocki was published.
Both projects were intended for military use of missile engines.
Shortly before the war, the Interim Scientific Advisory Committee (Tymczasowy Komitet Doradczo-Naukowy) was responsible for all missile technology projects for military use and coordinated all work.
The committee was founded in 1937, but after two years of activity, it was interrupted by the beginning of the war.
Other studies devoted to cosmonautics appeared in the Polish press after the war thanks to the work of the Polish Society of Astronautics (Polskie Towarzystwo Astronautyczne).
In the November 1954 issue of the magazine Problemmy refers for the first time to society with four very extensive articles dedicated to astronomicals.
One of them, by Prof. M. Subotowicze, proposed the creation of a society dedicated to cosmonautics.
At that time artificial satellite projects had already been launched and it was obvious that cosmic research was a discipline with prospects for the future.
Since the beginning of 1956 the Polish Astronautical Society (PTA) aspired to be part of the International Astronautical Federation (founded in 1951) and in the autumn of the same year the PTA became a full member.
The following year the first president of the PTA, Kazimierz Zarankiewicz (1902 - 1959), became the vice president of the International Astronautical Federation.
He served this position until his death in 1959.
Since 1956, the PTA participated significantly in the development of the RM probe rocket (Rakieta Meteorologicalzna), which was a success and became the first Polish rocket in which scientific research was carried out.
The first type RM-1 was completed in 1957 and was released for the first time on October 10, 1958.
The rocket had a height of 1,800 meters, about 80 cm in length and did not reach 5 kg in weight.
Later, the RM-1A version was completed and in the summer of 1959 aerial tests of the two-stage RM-2 rockets were initiated in the Błędów desert.
The rocket was 1.4 meters and weighed about 11.5 kg.
Another type of developing rocket was to be the subject of a real scientific study. The RM-34 rocket was to have a peak of 14.5 km and its mission would be to control the high wind.
However, work was suspended in 1962.
The successor of the first RM rockets was the Meteor-1 rocket, which was built in 1962 and 1965.
It was designed as a two-stage rocket, with a total length of 510 cm and an initial weight of 32.5 kg.
Three types were developed (called Meteor-1A, -1B and -1C), which differed from each other by the space available for scientific devices.
In the Meteor-1A rocket the space available for the volume was 0.4 liters, in the Meteor-1B of 0.34 liters and in the Meteor-1C of 0.62 liters.
The highest peak in all three types was 37 km.
Between 1965 and 1968 the Meteor-2 rocket was developed at the Air Institute, whose first air tests began in October 1970.
The Meteor-2 rocket had an initial weight of 380 kg and was capable of carrying a useful weight of 10 kg up to 60 km height.
Subsequently, the Meteor-2H and Meteor-3 versions were built.
It is also necessary to mention Poland's entry into COSPAR (Committee for Space Research) in 1960 and the formation of the COSPAR National Committee two years later.
In the framework of the Interkosmos programme, Poland joined in the research of cosmic space on Soviet artificial satellites and, in 1978, the Polish pilot Miroslav Hermaszewski became the second intercosmonaut after Vladimír Remek.
The suspension of the law on social work is not the solution.
Last week, the Constitutional Court suspended the law on social work.
The resolution sparked a heated discussion in society.
Of course, it will be interesting to examine the existing problem from a broader point of view.
Liberal economic systems in the EU, as in the globalised world, are based on the principle of greater economic and less regulatory competition.
Consequently, this means that different economic forms and national economic systems are in permanent conflict with each other.
The cause lies in the principle of free trade and the free and unlimited movement of private capital, together with unbridled financial speculation.
The effect of large differences in labour costs (wages) produces economic tensions.
Under this concept it is necessary to understand the situation in which the manufacturer, with the import of cheap goods, tries to shorten distances and to do so "provides a decrease" in the price of the competitor with the aim of making it with most of the market and thus increasing its profit margin.
On a large scale it means, for most entrepreneurs, moving production abroad, buying there cheaper or disappearing. The result is high unemployment in those countries where labour prices, compared to other economies, are higher.
Because private capital has no social responsibility and, by doing so, is not responsible for the unemployment that this phenomenon generates, the social expenditure of the state necessarily increases.
This whole situation encourages the total disinterest of entrepreneurs to pay taxes and compensate for the economic and social damage that they have caused in their desire to gain benefits.
The situation is universally known that there is no need to submit specific statistical data.
The unscrupulous practices of private capital create situations in certain economies in which the Governments of these countries are forced to compete with the objective of artificially reducing the social level of the population itself and thus attracting foreign capital to the country.
In other words, Governments make private capital available to their own people without taking into account social decline.
This is particularly evident in the changes in existing laws.
The aim is to force the population to accept the dictation of private capital, especially with regard to wages.
This takes place, on the one hand, through the system of economic obligation in the case of long-term unemployment; on the other, through the restricted right of employees to work rights.
The result is growing poverty along with the widening gap between the poor and the rich.
For a number of years, there have been food delivery points in Germany for poor people who cannot afford their own work.
The number of people receiving this kind of help is already at one million.
In the context of increasing the competitiveness of the German economy, there is a fairly frequent case: people employed with such low wages that the state must pay the rest to reach the minimum necessary to survive.
A scandal of this kind related to the situation of auxiliary employees in the German federal parliament was made public.
The savings measures of virtually all the states in the south of the EU lead, without a doubt, to the same situation. People, under pressure from an abyssal decline of their social level, are forced to emigrate as in the 19th century or to live badly on the edge of society, hoping that one day they will arrive in the private investor capital country.
Is it necessary to ask where it comes from?
In the case of other EU countries, then poverty goes from one country to another or never arrives, as Chinese, Indians, Brazilians, Turks, Moroccans, Egyptians or Africans continue to work for a small part of a European wage.
This also affects all of Latin America.
Liberal theories and the media affirm until the satiety that the state should not bring capital to the economy, that leading the economy leads to its failure.
Private capital defends with nails and teeth the thesis that the state should not intervene in the economy by interfering in control.
Next, it is necessary to ask whether private capital does not influence with its selfishness the political march and, therefore, throughout the state.
In this case the answer is clearly affirmative.
The test is the existence of lobbies, in practice very powerful and omnipresent, in all states.
The result is a desperate situation in the area of corruption, in mutual favours, in legislation that is practically reprobable everywhere but not punishable.
In Germany, the situation is as follows: State ministries, in the absence of financial means, are responsible for drafting bills to private legal enterprises, which are often linked to industry.
This type of bill is later passed in the Bundestag, the German parliament.
Thus, all power does not emanate from the people, as announced in the constitutions of Western democracies, but from the strong financial groups representing their own interests.
It is obvious that democracies with a liberal orientation quickly find themselves in a situation such as the one described by Appiános in his work The crisis of the Roman Republic in the times of Caesar and Pompeii: "The state had long been disintegrated and the administrations were busy with force".
In exchange for bribes, favors obtained illegitimately and help to finance stones or swords.
Bribery and corruption spread unimpededly and people went to the polls with the pulverized vote beforehand"... "there were no people in character who aspired to a post in the administration, so once, because of this disorganization, the state was eight months without consuls"... "He began to seriously speak of the fact that the only remedy for such a serious situation was autocracy and that it was necessary to choose an energetic man"... Although Appiános thought of Pompeii, Caesar went up to power and transformed democracy forever into autocracy.
The conclusion, in the same way as in ancient times, is that the present society is based on disregarded preferences of individual benefit without taking into account common interests.
Private capital is unable, in essence, to understand and claim the benefits of the whole society.
The result is the same as that of then, an unprecedented decadence of the elite, without any effort being made to reform it in depth.
The causes of the rise of fascist and communist regimes must therefore be sought in the unbridled liberalization of economic systems in the 19th and 20th centuries.
With respect to the current situation, it is possible to consider the disappearance of these systems for the benefit of a liberal democracy, as a definite pause, pending the next coup.
The real demolishing fact is that the current elite completely ignores the losses of hundreds of thousands in lives, social and humanitarian catastrophes that we have witnessed, as well as crimes against humanity, as we know them in ancient and most recent history.
The suspension of the Public Procurement Act is not the solution; at least not in the long term.
Under pressure from economic competition, both at international and within the EU, the government of the Czech Republic will be forced to continue to seek other ways to reduce the social level of the population.
This trend is therefore systemic.
The solution goes through concrete socio-political reforms, which reinforce both the participation of state capital and the influence of citizens in government and weaken the monopoly position of private capital in society for the benefit of the state.
