Argo is his third feature film, after "Goodbye Little, Goodbye" (2007) and the thriller "The Town. City of Thieves" (2010).
At the same time, it's Affleck's first film in which the action doesn't take place in Boston City, where it grew up.
Also, the sensitivity of capturing the atmosphere of the place was a feature that placed the directors of old films above Hollywood standards.
And Affleck shows it in Argo, where Tehran turns out to be in Canada.
The best scenes of the film take place in the streets, in the reconstruction of the true events. The introductory sequence of the taking of the embassy is impressive because of its synoptic ability that, at the same time, conveys the emotion of the disconcerting and the lack of prediction that arises when, somewhere, history takes a step forward.
Affleck and his collaborators have a similar effect on fictional scenes (the imposter team in Tehran's bazaar).
Too much action in too many places
