But I wonder why we need a library today.
We all have the Internet, tablets and e-books.
No one gets into those old-fashioned libraries for pleasure, right?
Spijkenisse, a dormitory town located at the gates of Rotterdam that hardly deserves a fleeting visit, has the dubious honor of having stood up with a record to forget.
The population of 80,000 has the lowest literacy rate in the Netherlands.
To counter this shameful situation, a few years ago it was decided to contribute in some way to the general culture and copy the seven fictitious bridges represented on euro banknotes in the form of decorated reinforced concrete miniatures.
The success of the educational offensive was limited.
And that's how the political leaders decided that there was only one possibility to improve statistics: a library had to be built!
Winy Maas, from the Dutch architecture studio MVRDV, a master in the art of bar diagrams and responsible for fun buildings as well as cynics, took the theme with his usual serenity and appeared at the presentation of the contest in 2003 with five books under his arm and a smile on his face.
And while the jury watched perplexed around him and shrugged his shoulders, Maas proceeded to stack the books by size forming a pyramid and concluded his brief speech with the following words: "Estimated fellow citizens:
Here you have it, my proposal for the book mountain of Spijkenisse, the so-called 'Boekenberg'."
Nine years later, the 30 million euro mountain rises in the planned location.
This is part of the revitalization project, which is completed with underground parking, a supermarket, a post office and a couple of residential and townhouse buildings.
In early November, the book mountain was awarded the second "Best Library of NL 2012" award.
In addition, the project is also nominated for the "Dutch National Wood Award 2012".
In this way, the small town without history, which to date had nothing more to offer than a postmodern pedestrian area and an incredibly ugly town hall behind whose white facade one would rather sense a central milk mill, now has a work of contemporary architecture.
But above all, Spijkenisse now has the first public cultural building in its history.
The long way to the book
The first impression is that it's a book paradise under a cheese.
It is true that there is an elevator that transports us right to the center of this mountain massif, but the true lovers of space and reading do not use it, but prefer to merge with its topography at every step of its climb to the top.
The fully glazed interior is bright and easy to cover with the view, the brick floor and the elegant headlights unequivocally support the public condition of the library.
The urban environment is perfect.
When you look up, you can see the banks of the park, dogs and boys and girls playing football.
And everywhere books, books, and more books.
"Normally book shelves are arranged along the façade and in the center there is a huge dark room that is usually somewhat uncomfortable and impersonal," says Winy Maas.
What we've done is put the classic spatial configuration up and take out the reading area from the inside to the outside.
The interior of the mountain is very well used: in the middle are the offices, the Internet library, the chess club, the environmental education center and the maintenance room.
Special mention deserve the black shelves that assume the functions of wall covering, parapet and railing at the same time.
The sight, the touch and the smell are strange.
Even architects and civil engineers more a day shake their heads when they hear about this unknown material.
"We wanted to work with recycled materials," explains Joop Trouborst, head of the project in the city of Spijkenisse.
And that's how one day, on a frisian farm, we encounter the right by-product from agriculture.
For many years now, in the greenhouses and in the fields of the Netherlands, a plastic fabric of scarce millimeters of thickness has been used as a basis for holding the roots of crops.
It is a cheap and efficient material.
This fine fabric lasts two seasons and then is discarded.
For the library, this fabric was taken, for the first time in such quantities, until it obtained plates of four centimeters thick.
With heat and pressure, the so-called agricultural plastic (KLP) changes color and becomes a dark, homogeneous and resistant material that smells like a new car mix and sports shoe.
After 105 steps you reach the top of the mountain.
At the end of this continuous road of almost 500 meters around the mountain awaits us the reward: from the cafeteria you not only have a fantastic view of the city, but also you can enjoy some tasty Dutch croquettes and their ficus planted in huge pots.
These create a pleasant environment at the same time that maintains the air humidity suitable for this mountain of literature.
Donations for a new soul
"Although it is hard to believe it given its large glazed surfaces, this building is an exemplary project in terms of ecology," says Trouborst.
The necessary heating and cooling are obtained from geothermal energy.
Although the mountain of books is situated under a huge pyramid of crystal, even on sunny days the sun only shines for a few hours inside.
The huge wooden fences located across the glass facade serve to give shade and absorb most of the sun's rays.
This creates a comfortable indoor climate.
The rest is a thing of automatic blinds.
Stefan Spermon, the sceptic worker in the Information Technologies sector, has already dared to set foot in the new library.
And Lisette Verhaig has also been there.
Also, Chinese traditional medicine teacher Cynthia Bogarde has visited the library. She qualifies the "Boekenberg" as the "late soul" of Spijkenisse.
The reason is that, on the occasion of the inauguration that took place a couple of weeks ago, all the inhabitants of the city were invited to donate a book from their private collection.
In this way, it is intended to fill, for the moment, the optical gaps of a library that does not yet have its complete archive; it currently has 70,000 copies.
The concept has shut down deep.
The shelves are full.
"There is nothing worse than an empty medium library," says architect Winy Maas.
"I believe that thanks to our initiative now all the inhabitants have a certain link with this building.
Everyone knows his book is part of the library.
Even if it's just there to adorn.
In this way, the MVRDV study has achieved quite a success in that discipline reigns which in the specialized argot is known as "creation of an identity".
The city of Spijkenisse has written a piece of the history of literature.
No matter how young and unbelieving it may be.
Finally a starting point to shape your identity.
