Manifestations that rival each other in Cairo reveal the tremendous division in which the country is plunged.
The future constitution, with sharia as a basis, is highly controversial.
The Egyptian president did not spare in pathetic.
"We must overcome the transition.
And that that happens is my responsibility, to the people and to God," he said on public television.
His speech was addressed to all the people, especially to Christian Coptics, Liberals, Illustrated Muslims and seculars.
All of them, who have been left without a remedy so far in a confused opposition, are afraid.
Fear of a theocracy on the banks of the Nile by the grace of the powerful Muslim community.
As Mohammed Mursi explains, almost asking for forgiveness, he has had to temporarily nullify the powers of the Constitutional Court and expand his "to be able to save the revolution".
However, neither Egyptians nor the whole world know very well what this 61-year-old engineer with a doctorate degree awarded by the University of Southern California really wants to save.
Do you intend to deprive the judiciary of its power?
In fact, the 234 articles, whose adoption has been forced by a constituent assembly composed of 100 predominantly Islamist members at a 15-hour night meeting, are truly worrisome.
As in previous constitutions, the draft also states that jurisprudence is based on the "principles of Islamic law".
What does that mean, "principles"?
This was and continues to be open to interpretation, and it seems that Islamists are going to take advantage of this vague formulation, as well as the margin of legal maneuver that it brings together, to impose a stricter interpretation of sharia.
This is at least what a new article suggests: in all issues relating to sharia it is mandatory to consult Al-Ashar University, the country's most important Islamic institution with great power in all Sunni Islam.
It does not have to be so, but this may mean that the clergy would control the legislation, something that - in fact - would result in the incapacity of the judiciary.
Much of the draft constitution is open to interpretation
What is also problematic is that it seeks to maintain military jurisdiction.
During the Mubarak dictatorship these courts served to exert harsh repression over the opposition.
Following the dictator's fall, up to 11,000 civilians were detained in military prisons.
As stated in the draft, the State must protect "the true essence of the Egyptian family" and "promote its morals and values".
This is such an imprecise formulation in legal terms that, with the help of this article, state institutions could even control the contents of cinematography and literature.
Clearly, this is nothing but censorship.
Indeed, no article explicitly establishes equality between men and women.
On the other hand, another prohibits offending or slandering Prophet Mohammed and his legacies.
However, it is not clear what an offence is and how it is to be punished.
Equally doubtful is the formulation that prohibits "offensive to people"
Is it enough for the president's cartoon or a joke about a lawyer?
Question of interpretation, like many other things in the draft that has been presented to Mursi for signature and that according to his words, "very soon" will be presented to the Egyptians to be submitted to referendum.
"The revolution is back"
The opposition has been closing ranks in front of the superiority of Islamists for weeks.
Ten thousand people gathered in an unusual harmony on Friday afternoon at Tahrir Square in Cario and swore to make the Act fail before it can enter into force.
"The revolution has returned and we will end up winning," says Hamdin Sabbahi, who takes third place on the list of presidential elections.
The Nobel Peace Prize and former Director of the International Atomic Energy Agency, Mohamed El-Baradei, stated that the draft constitution should be "in the bucket of history's garbage."
Through Twitter he accused Mursi's followers of wanting to lead a "state coup against democracy".
"When he convenes the referendum we will go to his palace and overthrow him," says oppositioner Jasser Said.
"We are not yet tired, the blood of our brothers has not yet been expiated", quoted in the Egyptian media the opposition politician Chaled Ali.
And several judges announced that they did not wish to supervise the referendum, so it would not be considered valid.
"The Quran is our constitution"
For its part, the well-organized Muslim community made an appeal to celebrate a counter-demonstration; in case not in Tahrir Square, but after a prayer on the other side of the Nile, before the University of Cairo.
Many women covered with a veil and supporters of the Salafists took part in the cry: "The people demand the application of divine law."
They demanded Mursi "clean the country", while proclaiming: "The Quran is our constitution".
A struggle for the sovereignty of the symbolic Tahrir Square, where everything began, would have caused a situation similar to that of a civil war.
It is clear that Mursi's supporters did not want to risk something like this happening.
The Muslim brothers stated that both those opposed to the draft constitution and its supporters would have expressed their views loud and clear.
Now would have come the time to let the people decide in the polls which direction the country should follow.
In this sense, it seems that the Islamist draft has guaranteed the majority.
"The expression 'Human Rights' doesn't even appear"
Hafez Abu Saeda is furious with this forced constitutional process that should actually have lasted until February and included all social forces.
This 48-year-old human rights lawyer and president of the Egyptian Human Rights Organization (EOHR) defended Muslim brothers when they were held in prison or had to face trial during the Mubarak dictatorship.
Not because he shared his ideology, but because for him human rights are indivisible.
For this reason he was beaten, convicted and imprisoned.
"And now the expression 'Human Rights' does not even appear in the new constitution," laments in a conversation with the newspaper "Welt am Sonntag".
The extension of Mursi's powers to the three powers of the State made this lawyer resign.
The measures taken are flagrant violations of the rules of democratic play and will lead Egypt to a new dictatorship.
"Instead of strengthening civil society, what the president has done is abolish it," Saeda laments.
However, democracy cannot function without civil society organizations.
Saeda feels abandoned, also by the international community, which observes the ideological struggle that is taking place on the banks of the Nile with a mixture of curiosity and tension.
This could turn against you.
A protestor at Tahrir Square warns: "You are conceiving a monster you cannot control."
Norwegian Rakfisk: The world's busiest fish?
The five million inhabitants of Norway enjoy one of the highest standards of living, not only in Europe but in the world.
Is it possible that the country's success has any connection with its greed for a highly oily fish?
Take a series of excessively cured cheeses.
Put them in the middle of a mountain of dirty, wet football clothes.
Leave it there for a week.
Then you can smell the paralyzing aroma of Rakfisk, one of Norway's exquisites.
I'm in the small town of Fagernes, about three hours from Oslo.
It's snowy. The landscape is spectacular and that smell, always present, floats in the air.
Rakfisk is salad trout that is fermented in water for a period of time, depending on how bad you prefer it, up to a year.
As it gets darker and colder, the Norwegians go to a festival that is held here in Fagernes, dedicated to this eating of the most, so to speak, captivating.
"It eats raw and then drinks an aquavit glass of a drink," says Havard Halvarsen, a city firefighter who is also what is known as the "General of Rakfisk", who organizes the festival.
Everywhere we see people eating this fish that is kept in small cubes and drinking from a drink important quantities of the drink.
"Some people like aquavit more than rakfisk," says Havard.
The drink can kill the smell.
I'll try some pieces.
If you can avoid passing it near the nose, it's not bad; it's not very different from a portion of sushi that has traveled a few kilometers by bus.
Rakfisk is a product that comes from a very different era, in which poverty struck Norway and where, before refrigeration, the fish was stored during the fall submerged in water and salt in hermetic barrels.
Later, in the middle of winter, when it is already well fermented, it comes out and, obviously with the inactive senses due to alcohol, it is eaten.
Just a generation ago, thousands of Norwegians were forced to leave their country in search of work, and emigrated mainly to the United States.
At present, the population is growing rapidly; more than 13% are immigrants, attracted by the abundance of jobs, high wages and a comprehensive system of social services.
A stream of inhabitants of Sweden, the old rival and even makes not too much richer than Norway, comes to this country to work.
Rakfisk is considered to be something important, an essential part, albeit rather ill-fouling, of Norway's past.
It is among the most expensive dishes you can buy.
But, in fact, everything is expensive. A beer cane or a sandwich cost you the fridge of 10€ ($14) each.
Norway does not usually appear on the international news agenda and most Norwegians like it to be so.
Here people are still unwilling to pronounce the name Anders Breivik, the far-right racist who shot and killed 77 people, including men, women and children.
Instead, they refer to the shooting as "the event of July 22".
It is very difficult for Norwegians to believe that in their peaceful country one of their own would be able to commit such cruelty and murder.
After much of Norway's present wealth, one of the world's largest oil and gas industries has grown since the early 1970s.
"But oil isn't the only reason we're doing so well," says Anna, our waitress, as she goes through rakfisk trays and that, with her long blonde apple and her amazing blue eyes, represents the image of Norwegian well-being.
"We are, as you say, prudent people."
His English, like most people in this country, is impeccable.
"We don't like to brag, we don't like ostentation."
Norway has managed its oil wealth with great caution; everything, except a small percentage of the money from this industry, is invested in a special fund for the benefit of future generations.
While everyone was wasting money they didn't have during the years preceding the financial crisis around the world, Norway kept the wallet tightly closed.
"While we can ski in winter and hiking in summer, we are happy," says Anna.
"And eat rakfisk", adds with an unwrapped carcass.
I'm in the snow doing queue to eat something; I've had enough rakfisk.
Now an elk burger is definitely something different and quite juicy to taste.
But at night, it's that stinking fish back.
The hotel I'm staying at is one of many places where a rakfisk dinner is held where the diners vote for the best fish, or perhaps the one that tests the nose pits most.
A television has connected live with a presenter who wears straw and is surrounded by rakfisk dishes.
Looks like the Eurovision competition.
"What are your scores for the best fish up there in the mountains, Thor-Juergen?"
"Here's our score, Havard."
There's laughter and applause.
A man falls out of the chair, maybe beaten by the aquavit.
Or maybe it's the vapors of all that fish.
Mexico: Enrique Peña Nieto Faces a Hard Start · Global Voices
As the incoming President of Mexico, Enrique Peña Nieto, prepares to take office, BBC correspondent Will Grant analyses the challenges facing the new president and the different expectations of his population.
Traffic in Mexico City is especially bad today.
In a city that, in the best circumstances, is already congested, a steel fence has been installed since Monday that cuts several of the main roads that lead to the city and that is causing enormous chaos on the roads.
The aim, however, was not to prevent workers from reaching their place of work, but to prevent protesters from reaching parliament.
On Saturday, Mexico's new president, Enrique Peña Nieto, will receive the presidential band and take over the nation's management.
He faces a complicated task.
Mexico has been achieving good economic results during the outgoing government of Felipe Calderón, but the country is plunged into a war against drug trafficking that has already claimed some 60,000 lives in six years.
"My government has a great commitment to the Mexican people to reduce violence," said Mr. Peña Nieto earlier this week to US President Barack Obama at the Oval Dispatch.
"I will propose a new security strategy that will allow us to achieve that goal."
Prior to coded with the president of the United States, Mr. Peña's previous political experience was as governor of his native state, Mexico.
A very populated state with rapid growth, which surrounds the capital; The opinions about the new leader are divided in this territory in which he used to move.
A sincere man
In the bucolic city of Valle del Bravo, for example, you are reminded with affection.
Its residents give it the credit for the growth of tourism on site and for the construction of infrastructure.
To get to the city you can drive along one of Mr. Peña Nieto's new roads, which is a huge improvement compared to the cracked and filled roads that were rehabilitated.
You can also see plaques with its name at the entrance to a modern sports sport and an impressive interactive museum on climate change.
"We trust that he can make a real and lasting change," says his friend and political ally Gabriel Olvera Hernández, MP of the party of Mr Peña Nieto, the PRI.
"In particular, in terms of security and economy, we look forward to the interesting and true change that our country so much needs."
After an uninterrupted period of 81 years in power, the PRI was disbanded by Vicente Fox in 2000.
The MP Olvera admits that after 12 years outside the presidential palace of Los Pinos, there are many expectations within the party regarding Enrique Peña Nieto.
It also rejects the opposition's lack of essence of the new president.
"He is a very sincere man, very committed and with an excellent vision of the country.
He's a fantastic statesman and, above all, he's a person who knows how to listen."
However, on the other side of the state that is not the impression that many people have about their former governor.
In Nezahualcoyotl, also known as Ciudad Neza, the contrast with the crowded streets of Valle del Bravo could not be greater.
Hidden under high highway sections is, in many ways, a suburb of Mexico City itself.
And the problems of the municipality are also hard and urban.
Earlier this year, military intervention was called for to assist in the fight against drug gangs operating in the neighbourhoods and violence against women is particularly serious.
In a desert plot, located next to a garbage dump, the bodies of dozens of murdered women have been abandoned in just the last two years.
More than 1,000 women were killed in the state of Mexico while Mr. Peña Nieto was the governor, a much higher rate than that of Ciudad Juárez, unfortunately famous for his violence and a place that is synonymous with murder of innocent women.
Mr. Peña Nieto's critics say, at best, that he was unable to address the problem of femicide while in office.
The most critical accuses his administration of making a blind eye.
In a concrete house, typical of the damaged neighborhood, Irinea Buendía has to make efforts to contain tears while showing me photographs of her deceased daughter, Mariana Luna.
According to the official version of the facts, Mariana committed suicide in 2010.
However, her family believes that her partner murdered her.
"When I got to her house, it looked like they cleaned her body," recalls Mrs. Buendía.
"There were signs that she had been beaten and rigor mortis had already appeared."
While his mother recounts the story, a photograph of Mariana looks from the walls, next to a cross on which a single word is read: Justice.
However, that's exactly what the family says he's been denied.
"The state authorities have treated me as if I were an old gossip, a rioter, a complaint.
What they want is for one simply to accept what they say and to shut up."
"But that cannot be so when there have been so many irregularities and so much negligence," he says.
The presidential band that President Peña Nieto will receive on Saturday will be accompanied by a huge responsibility.
Tens of thousands of families have been affected by violent crimes in Mexico for the past six years and the new president has promised to give them priority during his term of office.
"I hope it's the same kind of president that it was when I was governor," says PRI Olvera's deputy in Bravo Valley.
However, that is exactly what the families of the victims of Ciudad Neza fear most.
Bradley Manning did not report ill-treatment, according to prosecutors
Prosecutors try to deal with Bradley Manning's allegations of abuse while in prison
The trial focuses on Manning's period at Quantum Military Prison in Virginia
The defense wants the case dismissed on the grounds that Manning's incarceration was severe.
The army soldier is accused of stealing thousands of confidential documents.
Prosecutors tried to prove on Friday that Private Bradley Manning, accused of the greatest leak of confidential information in the history of the United States, lost multiple opportunities to report the ill-treatment he now claims to have suffered while in military detention.
During the interrogation that the prosecution conducted to Manning in a pre-trial hearing in Ft. Meade, Maryland, the prosecutor Commander Ashden Fein stated that the records of the weekly visits of officers of the unit Manning received for nine months of detention in Quantico, Virginia, do not show any complaints about the treatment he received.
The interrogation, which took place during a hearing following the defence's request that the case be dismissed since his imprisonment had been harsh and had already meant sufficient punishment, arrived one day after Manning had testified that he had thought about suicide while in detention.
The army intelligence analyst, arrested in June 2010, is accused of stealing thousands of confidential documents while serving in Iraq.
Later, WikiLeaks posted the material on the Internet.
WikiLeaks has never confirmed that Manning was the source of information.
In Friday's view, Fein reviewed with Manning the forms that the officers filled out after the visits to Manning during his arrest at the Quantico military prison, where he was imprisoned in maximum detention from July 2010 to April 2011.
The officers would have asked Manning questions and written down his answers.
When Friday Fein asked about the forms, Manning recognized that he had qualified the treatment given to him by the censors as "excellent" and the treatment received at the facilities in general as "very professional".
The forms show no complaints of ill-treatment, although the officers asked Manning directly about the treatment he received, Fein said.
Manning replied that he had expressed concern about some issues and that the visiting officers had spoken to him about those problems and had indicated that they would be dealt with, but that they did not record those issues in the register.
"They wrote 'no incidents' (after talking about problems) but this doesn't necessarily mean that I wouldn't have mentioned any problems," Manning said.
The judge, Colonel of the Denise Lind Army, also asked Manning why she had not reported the treatment she received during the January 2011 meeting with a council to examine the suicide intentions she had expressed in a form months earlier.
Manning replied that his intention during that meeting was to obtain a reduction in the "injury prevention" regime under which he was under.
The military said that they had placed him under this restrictive regime, which is below the level of surveillance for possible suicide, to ensure their protection and safety for others.
"I wanted the older state to know that I was okay and (I wanted) to stop being under injury prevention... so I could enjoy what, from my point of view, is a better quality of life," Manning said.
Manning testified on Thursday about his arrest in Iraq and his transfer to Kuwait, where he was detained for almost two months before being transferred to the military prison at the base of the marines in Quantico, Virginia, in July 2010.
He said he had considered suicide in Kuwait and that on one occasion he lost consciousness due to heat.
He said that the fact that he was not allowed to know what was happening to him or what was happening in the outside world was very distressing.
"My world was reduced only to Camp Aafjon, to that cage," Manning explained on Thursday.
"I thought I was going to die in that cage."
Manning stated that, once transferred to Quantico, he spent most of the days in a small cell, at least for 21 hours and often for 23 hours, without company.
Manning said he was only allowed to have a mattress, a blanket, a blouse, some clothes and his glasses.
He explained that he was trying to move all the time, since it was forbidden to sleep or even lie down during the day.
Manning claimed that he always had a light coming from outside pointing to his eyes while sleeping.
He said that if the censors couldn't see his face when he turned around at night, they would wake him up so he could turn around again.
Manning's lawyer filed in January 2011 a formal complaint about Manning's treatment.
Manning was transferred to Fort Leavenworth Military Prison in Kansas in April 2011.
On Friday, the judge asked Manning about an allegation she had made in her Thursday statement that, after being forced to sleep naked in her Quantico cell, she was forced during a morning count to remain barefoot in front of the jailers and other prisoners.
Manning had testified that he had never been given the opportunity to cover himself with the blanket during the count.
During the judge's interrogation on Friday, Manning said that he deduced from the order given to him by the jailer that he had to drop the blanket with which he could have covered, but recognized that no one had ordered him to drop it.
Manning testified on Thursday that he had been forced to sleep naked the night before because of an attempt to prove to an officer that he did not pose a danger to himself.
Manning stated that he had told the officer that he could have used the elastic of his underwear or his chanclas to self-injure himself but that he had not.
Manning testified that that night they had removed from their cell their underwear, their chancles and their glasses.
His lawyers were hopeful that the judge would at least take into account the experiences he had spent while in prison and drastically reduce his sentence in case he was convicted on the war council, which was expected to begin early next year.
The defence stated that it intends to cause Manning to plead guilty to minor crimes and to defend other allegations considered too extreme.
The hearing is scheduled to resume this weekend and prosecutors are expected to argue that the conditions of detention were justified.
The Pentagon has argued that Manning was held in accordance with the rules of application to any detainee in maximum custody in Quantico.
The charges against Manning include cooperation with the enemy, unlawfully provoke the publication of information on the Internet, leaking information from the national defense and theft of property or public records.
If he is found guilty of all charges, he could face life imprisonment.
My Mexican-American identity crisis
He claims that many were forced to leave Mexico due to lack of opportunities
Mexicans tend to criticize those who left; he says they remind Mexicans of those difficult times
Navarrette comments that Mexican-Americans are trapped between two worlds.
On a recent trip to Mexico City, he had barely come down the esplanade and reached the immigration processing area and was already completely confused.
Some posters indicated the way to two tails: one for "Mexicans" and the other for "Extranjeros".
I stayed there for a few seconds without being sure where I was supposed to go.
Having grown up in Central California, I've been called "Mexican" all my life.
It's ethnic tachygraphy, just as my Boston friends refer to themselves as "Irish" or my New York friends call themselves "Italian".
Later I decided "Mexico-American."
But this was Mexico.
And, in my grandfather's homeland, tachographs or scripts were not necessary.
He was just American.
I speak Spanish. I speak Spanish well enough to handle myself during an interview in this language.
But I don't have the vocabulary level of a native and I can't get rid of my American accent.
So I took my U.S. passport and put myself in the foreigner's tail.
I thought about that moment this week when Mexico's elected president, Enrique Peña Nieto, visited the White House to meet with President Obama.
On the agenda of the day, as always as the leaders of these two countries gather, it consisted of immigration, drugs and trade.
Peña Nieto was also looking forward to talking about the growth of the Mexican economy, one of the reasons why at the moment a Mexican is so likely to stay in Mexico as to venture to go to the United States.
He wants to partner with the United States and Canada and create a trade bloc in North America in the style of the European Union.
In addition, Peña Nieto promised to continue fighting drug cartels in Mexico, although he did not give details.
For Mexico, the relationship with the United States is complicated and full of grudge.
Probably most Americans never remember that in 1848 the United States invaded Mexico and forced its leaders to give up half of its territory at gunpoint.
But for Mexicans, who think in centuries, not in minutes, the elements that remind them are everywhere.
So, at the moment when a U.S. official says anything that carries the slightest criticism to Mexico, you start hearing complaints, both in the press and among the Mexican elite, about how Americans are usurping the sovereignty of their neighbors.
And the children of Moctezuma stand in war.
And yet, for Mexico, the relationship that really poses a whole challenge is that which they have with the more than 35 million Mexican-Americans living in the United States.
Are we talking grudge?
There's a lot.
In Mexico there are winners and losers, people for whom the country provides opportunities and others for whom it is not.
The only reason there are so many people of Mexican descent living in cities like Los Angeles, Las Vegas, Phoenix, Denver or San Antonio is that, at some point in our family tree, there was a person, maybe the father or mother or any of the grandparents, who was locked in the door of opportunity in Mexico and had to march north.
And most of the time that person fit into a particular profile: dark skin, a low level of study, coming from a poor people, etc.
We are their descendants and we are loyal to them.
Not Mexico.
And, even though we may now be living the American dream, having gone to good schools and had good jobs, we can never lose sight that what we are living is that, the American dream, and not the Mexican one.
Sometimes our identity may not be clear, but our loyalty is.
It's for the United States.
In addition, we are aware that many of the Mexicans belonging to the elite of the ruling class do not like us.
The feeling is mutual.
They see us as a reminder of a humiliating defeat and they look at us over the shoulder as if we were from a lower category that is not Mexican enough.
Our Spanish will never be good enough and our ties to Mexico will never be strong enough.
In his view, our existence is synonymous with failure.
If our families hadn't failed in Mexico, they wouldn't have left.
And now we wouldn't be trapped behind this silk curtain, living well in the United States but still as lonely souls.
My wife, who was born in Guadalajara and came legally to the United States when she was a girl, reminds me that there is this rock between Mexicans and Mexican-Americans because the former know more solidly who they are and the latter it bothers them.
Although she is a citizen of the United States, she is considered to be part of the two countries.
Meanwhile, many Mexican-Americans I know feel that they are not part of either.
We love listening to the Mexican group Los Tigres del Norte, but also to Bruce Springsteen.
You have the best of every country, but you're not rooted in any of them.
In Mexico they see us as Americans.
And in the United States we are considered Mexicans.
Now, to further complicate things, so I learned during my trip, some Mexican leaders and some intellectuals want to reconnect with the diaspora.
They want Mexican-Americans to work as improvised Mexican ambassadors, representing their interests in the United States.
We would tell our American comrades how fantastic it is to visit that country and pressure the political leaders to strengthen their ties with Mexico.
Yes, of course...
That's not gonna happen.
There's too much grudge.
And, with wage inequality, galloping corruption and drug violence, many of us aren't so sure it's a fantastic country.
I'm afraid you're gonna be alone with this idea, folks.
It's fair.
If some Mexicans are not yet prepared to forgive the United States for the way they treated Mexico a century and a half ago, then they have to accept the fact that some Mexican-Americans are still resented for how their family members were treated a lot less time ago.
Hmm.
Maybe we're more Mexicans than I thought.
Old battles, new Middle East
The ceasefire between Israel and Hamas could well be an unlikely basis for peace
Can there ever be lasting peace between Arabs and Jews in the Middle East?
Another bloodshed that seems to indicate that any hope is in vain.
In the midst of the futile and usual discussions about who started first, many buildings have been reduced to rubble; more than 140 Palestinians, most of them civilians, and six Israelis have been killed and, for the first time, missiles from Gaza have fallen near Tel Aviv, the Israeli metropolis, and the holy city of Jerusalem.
But, despite the fact that Israelis and Palestinians seem to be anchored in their old conflict, everything around them in the Middle East is changing.
The Arab spring has left it all torn whether they like it or not, Palestinians and Israelis have been trapped in the regional turmoil.
Maybe this will make your fight even more bloody than before.
However, there are reasons to think that their lethal standstill situation could disembark.
A war that is neither lost nor won
At first glance, optimism now seems very difficult to justify.
Even if the ceasefire agreed on 21 November is maintained, this week's clashes have reinforced the hawks on both sides.
Hamas leaders, the Islamist movement that has ruled Gaza since 2007, will claim to have forced the Israelis to withdraw, despite the fact that Gaza has received a good beating.
And despite killing some of its leaders and putting the 1.7 million inhabitants of Gaza under pressure in one of the most miserable and populated corners of the planet, Israel has not been able to end Hamas.
In fact, Hamas is gaining ground in the West Bank, the other part of Palestine currently ruled by its ruthless rivals of Fatah, the most moderate Palestinian faction.
In addition, Hamas leaders could conclude that time plays in their favor.
Since Islamists have been gaining influence throughout the Arab world, Hamas has made rich and powerful friendships.
Turkey, a renaissant regional power that had previously been the closest Muslim ally to Israel, has embraced the cause of Hamas. Qatar, one of the richest and most dynamic states in the Gulf, has also done so.
The exulting Hamas members say that the half-Islamic moon is surrounding Israel, from Lebanon to the north, where the Hizbulah militia party dominates, passing through Syria, where rebels of an increasingly Islamist trend could overthrow Bashar Assad, until they reach Jordan, where Hamas' allies are threatening the king.
Above all in the southern flank of Israel, the growth of Muslim Brotherhood led by President Muhammad Morsi in Egypt, unlike the most populated and fundamental of Arab countries, has changed the balance of the region.
Hosni Mubarak, the lay despot who ruled Egypt for 30 years until his fall in 2011, did not have much time for Hamas.
On the other hand, the Muslim Brothers are Hamas brothers' cousins and their leaders depend more on popular opinion.
In future diplomatic actions, Hamas may emerge as a protagonist to which it cannot be excluded, not even Israel and the United States.
Meanwhile, Israel's hard wing will draw the opposite conclusion.
As far as the military issue is concerned, they have put Hamas in place.
Israel's anti-missile system Iron dome has proven its effectiveness and many of Hamas' missiles have been destroyed.
The Israelis will sleep more calmly... for some time.
With regard to diplomacy, the United States is stronger than ever; many European countries also blamed Hamas for having begun the last wave of violence.
First of all, Israel has prospered. Especially under the rule of Benjamin Netanyahu, a prime minister who has largely ignored the peace process.
Although rockets fired from Gaza have ended the lives of some 30 Israelis since 2004, Israel has not had too many suicide bombers, partly thanks to the barrier that runs across the West Bank, the main piece of an aspiring territory to become a state of Palestine, and it protects the Jewish settlements that continue to grow despite the fact that, according to international law, they are illegal.
Mr Netanyahu, whose Likud party has joined an even tougher line group led by Avigdor Lieberman in the pre-election period on 22 January, is in a good position.
Why spoil those Palestinian torments by giving them a state of their own?
If they really ruled in the West Bank, wouldn't they fire rockets like their fellow countrymen in Gaza?
It's better to have them behind that wall and give them a good blow if they raise their heads.
Perhaps the hard wing is imposed, although the Arab spring could alter its calculations.
Although Islamists who take power in Egypt and elsewhere do not have much appreciation for Israel, their priority will be to address internal difficulties.
Israel's defence budget is larger than that of its four Arab neighbours together.
Starting a war with the superpower of the area will hardly help the new Arab governments to improve their economies.
That pragmatic Mr. Morsi has worked with Barack Obama to get the ceasefire is a good wish and could mark the start of something.
Israelis should also think in the long term.
With the rest of the Arab world becoming more democratic, depriving Palestinians of their right to self-determination means creating a powder that one day will explode in the territories occupied by Israel, the same way that this week exploded a bus in Tel Aviv.
The repression is already undermining democracy in the Jewish state and demography worsens the situation as the Arab population increases.
The cruel missions against Gaza every two or three years to reject Hamas will pay an increasing diplomatic toll.
Both sides need a push from outside the conflict.
