First, like many people, I assumed that, now that we have more time for leisure, boredom would be a relatively recent phenomenon.
But, as Peter Toohey, professor of Greek and Roman History at the University of Calgary, Canada, and author of the book "Boredom: A Lively History" ("The boredom, an animated story") published in 2011 by Yale University Press, is not so.
"In fact, the story of boredom is very extensive," he says.
In the walls of Pompeii there are graffiti in Latin about boredom dating back to the 1st century AD.
We must also consider how we define boredom.
"The problem is that it has already been defined and discussed in a variety of ways," says John D. Eastwood, Professor of Psychology at York University in Ontario, Canada.
After examining the published research and putting the idea before a discussion group of 100 people, Professor Eastwood and his colleagues defined boredom as the experience of "desiring, but not being able, to participate in an activity that fills you".
He claims that the difference between boredom and apathy is that the person doesn't do anything but wants to do it.
He points out that with apathy there is no desire to do anything.
The main experience of boredom, he says, is "the alteration of the attention process, associated with a low mood and a feeling that time passes slowly."
boredom can sound terribly like depression.
However, Professor Eastwood says that, although they may be related, people who are bored tend to see the problem as a matter of the environment or the world, while people who are depressed consider it to be the problem they have.
Sometimes we think we're bored, when what happens to us is that we have problems concentrating.
In his study "The Unengaged Mind: Defining Boredom in Terms of Attention", published in the September edition of the magazine Perspectives on Psychological Science, Professor Eastwood and his colleagues referred to an earlier experiment in which participants listened to a tape of a person who read the article of a journal.
Some groups listened in the adjoining room to a television program with all volumes that had no relation, others listened to it with the low volume, so it was barely perceptible, while the third group did not listen to the audio at any time.
The group that listened to the program with low volume showed more boredom than the other two groups; it cost them to concentrate, but they were not sure why and attributed it to boredom.
"When you try to focus on a difficult or interesting task, altered attention can lead to boredom," said Mark J. Fenske, Professor of Neuroscience at the University of Guelph, Ontario, and one of the authors of the study.
"On the other hand, when you're doing something boring, like detecting defective parts in a manufacturing line, a music that distracts you can help you not get bored."
"In fact, we now know that moving or squeaking, actions that are often interpreted as a sign of boredom, can actually help to fight it, as they make that person physically more alert."
"Research shows that those children who are allowed to move learn more and retain more information than those who are forced to be quiet," says Professor Fenske.
We all know what it's like to get bored at some point: the delay of an airplane, a monotonous speaker, a particularly boring film.
But some people are more likely to get bored than others.
To help measure it, some researchers developed in the 1980s a "scale of tendency to boredom".
The scale includes issues such as "many of the things I have to do are repetitive and monotonous" and "there are so many things that interest me that I don't have time to do everything."
Stephen Vodanovich, Professor of Psychology at West Florida University, says that, using these scales, researchers have discovered that boys are more likely to get bored than girls, and specifically need more external and varied stimulation.
But, in general, teenagers are a kind of group that gets bored quite easily.
In 1991, Reed Larson, a professor of human and community development at the University of Illinois, conducted an experiment in which 400 adolescents and their parents were contacted seven to eight times a day through a search.
